        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>CX330 has never been observed at wavelengths longer than 22 microns, but has 
an SED that peaks at roughly the same wavelength and at roughly the same 
intensity as the known FUor V1515 Cyg. Sandell &amp; Weintraub (2011) mapped V1515 
Cyg at 850 microns 
with SCUBA and found a peak intensity of 130 mJy/beam. The beam size of ALMA 
with a resolution of 0.15" is 100 times smaller than that used in SCUBA 
observations, so we 
would expect V1515 Cyg to have a central intensity of ~1 mJy/beam. Because 
CX330 is roughly the same brightness in mid-IR wavelengths as V1515 Cyg, we 
use 1 mJy/beam as the estimated source brightness.

As discussed in the Science Case, a pessimistic distance of 2 kpc and a 
velocity of 100 km/s would result in a proper motion of ~0.015"/year. In 
order to securely establish a first epoch to measure the proper motion of 
CX330, we need to place the centroid 
accurately to 0.003". Using the approximation that centroiding is accurate to 
roughly the angular resolution divided by the signal to noise ratio of the 
observation, we request a long enough integration time for a signal to noise 
ratio of 50 in the third quartile of weather. If the flux level is 
significantly below what we expect from comparing CX330 to similar FUor 
systems, we will be better able to plan ALMA observations in the future 
once ALMA is brought to full capabilities. If the flux level is as high 
as we expect it
it to be, then we will also have a 1st epoch to use for proper motion 
measurements. 

If CX330 has a smaller circumstellar envelope than V1515 Cyg or other FUors, 
it could be substantially fainter at these wavelengths than V1515 Cyg. A 
sensitivity of 0.02 mJy/beam is sufficient to resolve the envelope of dus 
and gas suspected to be around CX330
at with a SNR of 5 if CX330 is a factor of several fainter than V1515 Cyg 
at this frequency band,
so even if this object is an order of magnitude fainter than expected, we 
should still have a secure detection of CX330 which will be important for 
future observational plans.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
