    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>A new candidate FU Orionis star has been identified by the Chandra Galactic 
Bulge Survey, an X-ray survey of the Galactic Bulge. This object, 
CXOGBS J173643.8-282122, undergoes an optical outburst of at least 6 magnitudes
which persists over 3 or more years and shows a large infrared excess. 
Such outbursts, occurring in pre-Main Sequence stars, are thought to be the 
result of a disk instability which causes a large increase in the accretion 
rate which lasts for decades. The circumstellar envelope feeding the accretion 
disk of these forming stars can extend for thousands of AU, wide enough to be 
resolved by ALMA. Resolving the dust envelope would confirm this unusual 
object's classification. Measuring the position accurately would also provide a first epoch
for accurate proper motion that 
could be used to determine if this object was born in a star forming region 
and is in its current position as a result of a dynamical interaction, or if 
it was formed in the field. </prp:abstract>
